    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-08-11T19:07:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-08-11T19:07:00-05:00" n="487"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d487">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">861.00/5021: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Japan</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_MRS1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Morris</hi>
                    </persName>), <hi rend="italic">temporarily at Omsk, to the <gloss type="to"
                            >Secretary of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]<note n="6" xml:id="d487fn6">Complete text,
                                <hi rend="italic">ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_410">p.
                            410</ref>.</note>
                    </seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Omsk</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-08-12T05:00:00+04:53">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 12, 1919, 5 a.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                        <lb/>[Received August 13, 7:34 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <p>I recommend the release of the notes at Vladivostok although I appreciate the
                    difficulties suggested in your August 8, 7 p.m. I doubt whether the <persName
                        corresp="#p_KAAV1">Kolchak</persName> Government can or will use them under
                    present conditions; but if requested I think Heid should be instructed to
                    deliver them. The establishment of the yen in Eastern Siberia and Manchuria
                    would in my judgment be most unfortunate. We have no American banks interested
                    in the proposal to buy rubles; the French and British banks will, I think,
                    accept the proposal; and the Japanese banks will, of course, refuse.</p>
                <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MRS1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Morris</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
